Ashleyâ€™s primary job will be upgrading and testing robotic tools used to conduct experiments and do maintenance on the ship. Life on the ISS is busy and isolating%2C but Ashley says they are excited to be one the few people to see the earth from orbit.%0A

In 2016%2C Ashley was one of over 18%2C000 candidates applying to the astronaut training program at NASA%2C and one of only 10 candidates chosen. Training to be an astronaut takes two years%2C which Ashley spent flying training jets%2C learning medical and survival skills%2C and learning Russian. To get used to zero gravity%2C Ashley and other recruits flew in a plane that creates around 20 seconds of weightlessness each time it climbs and dives. Because so many people get sick experiencing zero gravity for the first time%2C astronauts jokingly call this the â€œvomit cometâ€ or the â€œweightless wonder.â€ To practice spacewalks%2C Ashley spent hours working underwater in a massive pool.
